2026-06-09 18:26:15 [INFO] Bot: content="Class! Today we're going to explore another fascinating experiment involving hydrogen peroxide. Are you all ready?\n\n**The Experiment:**\n\nWe're going to create a **Foam Factory** using hydrogen peroxide and yeast! Yes, you heard that right – yeast!\n\n**What's the reaction?**\n\nHydrogen peroxide is a strong oxidizing agent, which means it can easily release oxygen gas when broken down. Yeast, on the other hand, loves to feed on sugars and produce carbon dioxide gas as a byproduct.\n\nWhen we mix hydrogen peroxide with yeast, something amazing happens! The yeast starts to break down the sugar molecules in the hydrogen peroxide solution, producing carbon dioxide gas. This reaction is called **fermentation**.\n\nBut here's the cool part: when the oxygen gas from the hydrogen peroxide reacts with the carbon dioxide produced by the yeast, it creates a **foam**!\n\nH2O2 + Yeast → CO2 + O2 (oxygen bubbles) → Foam!\n\n**The Experiment:**\n\n1. Mix 10 mL of hydrogen peroxide solution with 5 g of sugar in a clean glass container.\n2. Add 1-2 teaspoons of active dry yeast to the mixture.\n3. Stir gently and observe what happens.\n4. As the reaction progresses, you should start to see bubbles forming on the surface!\n5. Keep stirring until the foam becomes thick and creamy.\n\n**What are we observing?**\n\nAs the hydrogen peroxide decomposes and the yeast ferments the sugar, we're seeing:\n\n1. **Foam formation**: The oxygen gas released from the hydrogen peroxide reacts with the carbon dioxide produced by the yeast, creating a thick, creamy foam.\n2. **Bubbles forming on the surface**: These bubbles are oxygen gas being released from the solution.\n\n**Why is this experiment cool?**\n\nThis experiment shows us how two different reactions can occur simultaneously to produce an amazing result – foam! It's like a mini-chemistry factory in a jar!\n\n**Tips and Variations:**\n\n* Use different types of sugar, such as honey or maple syrup, to see if they affect the reaction.\n* Experiment with different ratios of hydrogen peroxide to yeast to see how it affects the foam formation.\n* Try adding food coloring to the mixture to create colorful foam.\n\nNow, are there any questions before we start the experiment?" additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={'model': 'llama3.1:8b-instruct-q8_0', 'created_at': '2026-06-09T15:26:15.1800497Z', 'done': True, 'done_reason': 'stop', 'total_duration': 333969010200, 'load_duration': 31220400, 'prompt_eval_count': 567, 'prompt_eval_duration': 3745000000, 'eval_count': 482, 'eval_duration': 330188000000, 'logprobs': None, 'model_name': 'llama3.1:8b-instruct-q8_0', 'model_provider': 'ollama'} id='lc_run--019eacf8-b5f9-7db1-9f7e-104844f4c838-0' tool_calls=[] invalid_tool_calls=[] usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 567, 'output_tokens': 482, 'total_tokens': 1049}
