2026-06-24 12:25:27 [INFO] User: Explain the alkaline metals and water reaction. Why other metals are not so reactive?
2026-06-24 12:25:27 [INFO] Bot: {"request_type":"theory","short_answer":"Alkali metals react violently with water because they have one valence electron that they 'want' to lose to achieve a stable configuration, and this happens very easily due to their low ionization energy.","explanation":"When an alkali metal (like lithium, sodium, or potassium) touches water, it undergoes a rapid redox reaction. The metal atoms give up their outer electron to become positive ions, while the water molecules are split into hydrogen gas and hydroxide ions ($H_2O + Metal \rightarrow Metal-hydroxide + H_2$). This process releases a lot of energy as heat. Because alkali metals have very large atomic radii and only one valence electron, it takes very little energy to remove that electron (low ionization energy). Other metals, like iron or copper, are much less reactive because their outer electrons are held much more tightly by the nucleus, making it harder for them to react with water under normal conditions.","examples":[],"experiment":{"kind":"none","reason":"The question is a theoretical inquiry about chemical properties and periodic trends; no experimental procedure was requested."},"certainty":"high"}
